On 1 August 1948, a [[Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631]] of [[Air France]] went missing over the [[Atlantic Ocean]], killing all 52 people on board. The accident led to the withdrawal of the Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631 from service by Air France. It was the deadliest aircraft accident in the Atlantic Ocean at the time and also the deadliest suffered by that type of aircraft.

==Aircraft==
The accident aircraft was [[Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631]] [[aircraft registration|F-BDRC]], ''Lionel de Marnier'', [[manufacturer's serial number|msn 06]].<ref name=Aeroplane0114>{{cite journal |title=Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631 |journal=Aeroplane |issue=January 2014 |pages=pp.102-03 |publisher=Kelsey Publishing |location=Cudham |issn=0143-7240}}</ref><ref name=ASN010848>{{cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19480801-1 |title=F-BDRC Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref> The aircraft had been involved in a previous incident on 31 October 1945, when operating a flight from [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil to [[Montevideo]], Uruguay and [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina. The propeller of No. 3 engine separated in flight, damaging No. 2 engine. A propeller blade sliced a {{convert|3|m|ft|0|adj=on}} hole in the cabin, killing two passengers. A fire started and an emergency landing was made in the [[Laguna de Rocha]], Uruguay.<ref name=ASN311045>{{Cite web |url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19451031-1 |title=F-BDRC Accident description |publisher=Aviation Safety Network |accessdate=3 December 2013}}</ref>

==Accident==
The aircraft departed from [[Fort de France]], [[Martinique]] at 14:50 [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]] on 31 July, and was due to arrive at [[Port-Etienne]], [[French West Africa]] at 01:00 GMT on 1 August. It was carrying a crew of twelve and 40 passengers.<ref name=Times020848/> It was reported that a [[mayday]] had been received by an American radio station in the [[Azores]] just after midnight on 1 August. The aircraft's position was estimated as {{convert|1100|nmi|km}} north of the [[Cape Verde Islands]].<ref name=Times030848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=THE MISSING FRENCH FLYING-BOAT |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=3 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51140 }}</ref> Two Air France aircraft, a [[French Air Force]] aircraft and a [[French Navy]] ship were sent to search for the aircraft.<ref name=Times020848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=52 ON BOARD MISSING SEAPLANE |day_of_week=Monday |date=2 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51139 }}</ref> The [[United States Coast Guard]] sent {{USCGC|Campbell|WPG-32|6}} to assist in the search.<ref name=Times060848/> The Portuguese authorities allowed aircraft searching for the missing Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631 to use the [[Am<U+00ED>lcar Cabral International Airport|Ilha do Sal Airport]], which was not then open to traffic.<ref name=Times040848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Missing French Flying Boat |day_of_week=Wednesday |date=4 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51141 }}</ref> Two [[Portuguese Air Force]] [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]]es also joined the search.<ref name=Times060848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=MISSING FLYING-BOAT |day_of_week=Friday |date=6 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51143 }}</ref> The [[United States Air Force]] sent a Flying Fortress and seven [[Boeing B-29 Superfortress]]es to join the search.<ref name=Times050848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=SEARCH FOR FRENCH FLYING BOAT |day_of_week=Thursday |date=5 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51142 }}</ref>

On 3 August, the French [[weather ship]] ''Leverrier'' reported receiving a distress message from the aircraft. A second message was received early the next morning. The American Flying Fortress also reported receiving a "faint and garbled" distress message that day.<ref name=Times050848/> USCGC ''Campbell'' reported finding two seats from the aircraft at a position {{convert|1570|nmi|km}} east of Puerto Rico. An aircraft later reported seeing wreckage {{convert|15|nmi|km}} from the position the seats were found.<ref name=Times060848/> The search for survivors was called off on 9 August.<ref name=Times100848>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=SEARCH FOR FLYING-BOAT ABANDONED |day_of_week=Tuesday |date=10 August 1948 |page_number=4 |issue=51146}} </ref> Following the accident, which was the worst aircrash in the Atlantic Ocean at the time and also the worst ever suffered by the Lat<U+00E9>co<U+00E8>re 631,<ref name=ASN010848/> the type was withdrawn from service by Air France.<ref name=Aeroplane0114/>

